nts from alternative justice agencies, Amanda Nelund finds that alternative programs neither reproduce dominant justice system norms nor provide complete alternatives. Instead, formal and informal practices reflect the tension between neoliberal and social justice approaches. A Better Justice? calls attention to the potential that alternative programs have for both alignment with and opposition to criminal justice norms. It is in the potential points of resistance that we can find improved strategies – and ultimately, greater social justice for criminalized women in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitationzManitobazWinnipeg. 0aFemale offendersxServices forzManitobazWinnipeg. 0aFemale offenderszManitobazWinnipegxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486364340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774863643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774863643/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles